"1325":"1325","Bef 9 October 1375":"vóór 9 oktober 1375","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1343":"1343","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1408":"1408","Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brome, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brome, Suffolk, England":"Brome, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1350–1420":"about 1350–1420","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1355–1432":"1355–1432","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","BEF 1408":"before 1408","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","Abt 1350":"about 1350","1325":"1325","Bef 9 October 1375":"before 9 October 1375","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1343":"1343","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1408":"1408","Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Brome, Suffolk, England":"Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Braham Jr was born about 1350, in Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John de Braham, was 31 and his mother, Margery Tye, was 26. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. Joan De Braham. He died in 1420, in his hometown, at th